Tmi: first two books of the Histories relate the events of the eighteen months between December (68) and July (69). The opening days of the year 69 had seen Galba's fall : Otho, his successor, had reigned but three months when he determined not to survive the defeat of his troops by the northern army of Vitellius: and the summer found Vitellius in Rome and Vespasian already proclaimed Emperor in the east. That victorious general would apparently have accepted the rule of Galba: but he would not serve an Otho, much less a Vitellius. Counselled and aided by Mucianus, the governor of Syria, he resolved to assert his claims to the purple, and to maintain them in Italy by force of arms. The later books of the Histories are the story of the establishment of the Flavian dynasty: they describe two and touch upon the third of the three great wars which ushered in that dynasty—the war in Italy, the war in the North, and the war in the East.
